{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3526681,"name":"Andrii Bessarab","username":"andriibessarab","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/andriibessarab/{size}/258546_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-14T02:08:39.232Z","cooked":"<p>Hey everyone!</p>
<p>We’ve been testing our vision system and decided to utilize <span class="abbreviation">YAGSL<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Yet Another Generic Swerve Library"></template></span>’s <code>getMaximumModuleAngleVelocity()</code>. When we output the value in radians per second, we get an astonishing <em>12000 rad/s</em> <em>(~2000 rotations)</em>! This is very impressive, but it is definitely not accurate.</p>
<p>I found how <span class="abbreviation">YAGSL<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Yet Another Generic Swerve Library"></template></span> is calculating the maximum angular velocity:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public AngularVelocity getMaxAngularVelocity() {
    if (maxAngularVelocity == null) {
        maxAngularVelocity = RotationsPerSecond.of(
            RadiansPerSecond.of(angleMotor.getSimMotor().freeSpeedRadPerSec)
                .in(RotationsPerSecond) * configuration.conversionFactors.angle.gearRatio);
    }
    return maxAngularVelocity;
}
</code></pre>
<p>This calculation appears reasonable, but when I looked at WPILib’s value for the NEO motor’s maximum rotation (under no load):</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">/**
 * Return a gearbox of NEO motors.
 *
 * @param numMotors Number of motors in the gearbox.
 * @return A gearbox of NEO motors.
 */
public static DCMotor getNEO(int numMotors) {
    return new DCMotor(
        12, 2.6, 105, 1.8, Units.rotationsPerMinuteToRadiansPerSecond(5676), numMotors);
}
</code></pre>
<p>It specifies <em>5676 rotations per minute</em>, which would indeed explain why the value we get is so high. But is this really reasonable?</p>
<p>Any thoughts or insights would be greatly appreciated!</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":9,"updated_at":"2025-02-14T02:09:07.462Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":21,"reads":180,"readers_count":179,"score":141.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":491642,"topic_slug":"yagsl-calculates-our-max-ang-velocity-to-be-12000rad-s","display_username":"Andrii Bessarab","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":58460,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"4951 Alumni"},"post_url":"/t/yagsl-calculates-our-max-ang-velocity-to-be-12000rad-s/491642/1","custom_user_title":"4951 Alumni","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3526691,"name":"Christopher149","username":"Christopher149","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/838e76/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-02-14T02:14:54.440Z","cooked":"<p>~6000 <span class="abbreviation">RPM<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Revolutions Per Minute"></template></span> makes sense for the motor, which would be 100 rotations per second (6000 / 60), which with some reduction in the swerve module should be even less than 100, so something is wrong somewhere.</p>
